quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to include the <iostream> header:
[!raw!]
#include <{0}>

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Your First C++ Program[/h1]

A C++ program is a collection of commands or statements.

Below is a simple code that has "Hello world!" as its output.[code format="cpp" codeId="166"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
  cout << "Hello world!";
  return 0;
}[/code]
Let's break down the parts of the code.[code format="cpp" ]#include <iostream>[/code]
C++ offers various headers, each of which contains information needed for programs to work properly. This particular program calls for the header [b]<iostream>[/b].
The [b]number sign (#)[/b] at the beginning of a line targets the compiler's pre-processor. In this case, [b]#include[/b] tells the pre-processor to include the [b]<iostream>[/b] header. 
[note]The [b]<iostream>[/b] header defines the standard stream objects that input and output data.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to use names from std namespace:
[!raw!]
#include <iostream>
{0} namespace {1};

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Your First C++ Program [/h1]

The C++ compiler [b]ignores [/b]blank lines.
In general, blank lines serve to improve the code's readability and structure. 
[note]Whitespace, such as spaces, tabs, and newlines, is also ignored, although it is used to enhance the program's visual attractiveness.[/note]
[code format="cpp" codeId="167"]#include <iostream>
[b]using namespace std;[/b]

int main()
{
  cout << "Hello world!";
  return 0;
}[/code]
In our code, the line [b]using namespace std;[/b] tells the compiler to use the [b]std [/b](standard) [b]namespace[/b]. 
[note]The [b]std [/b]namespace includes features of the C++ Standard Library.[/note]

[h1]Main[/h1]

Program execution begins with the main function, [b]int main()[/b].[code format="cpp" codeId="168"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

[b]int main()
{
  cout << "Hello world!";
  return 0;
}[/b][/code]
Curly brackets { } indicate the beginning and end of a function, which can also be called the function's body. The information inside the brackets indicates what the function does when executed.
[note]The entry point of every C++ program is [b]main()[/b], irrespective of what the program does.[/note]

[h1]Your First C++ Program  [/h1]

The next line, [b]cout << "Hello world!";[/b] results in the display of "Hello world!" to the screen.[code format="cpp" codeId="169"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
  [b]cout << "Hello world!";[/b]
  return 0;
}[/code]
In C++, [b]streams [/b]are used to perform input and output operations.
In most program environments, the standard default output destination  is the screen. In C++, [b]cout [/b]is the stream object used to access it. 
[b]cout [/b]is used in combination with the insertion operator. Write the insertion operator as [b]<<[/b] to insert the data that comes after it into the stream that comes before.
[note]In C++, the [b]semicolon [/b]is used to terminate a statement. Each statement must end with a [b]semicolon[/b]. It indicates the end of one logical expression.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to output "Hello, world!" on the screen:
[!raw!]
{0} << "Hello, world!";

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Statements[/h1]

A [b]block [/b]is a set of logically connected statements, surrounded by opening and closing curly braces.
For example: [code format="cpp"]{
  cout << "Hello world!"; 
  return 0;
}[/code]
[note]You can have multiple statements on a single line, as long as you remember to end each statement with a [b]semicolon[/b]. Failing to do so will result in an error.[/note]

[h1]Return[/h1]

The last instruction in the program is the [b]return [/b]statement. The line [b]return 0;[/b] terminates the [b]main()[/b] function and causes it to return the value 0 to the calling process. A non-zero value (usually of 1) signals abnormal termination.[code format="cpp" codeId="170"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
  cout << "Hello world!";
 [b] return 0;[/b]
}[/code]
[note]If the return statement is left off, the C++ compiler implicitly inserts "[b]return 0;[/b]" to the end of the main() function.
Tap [b]Continue [/b]to learn more about functions, return, and other topics.[/note]
